# Vendor Contract Register
# Build a contract management solution with RALPH, then demo renewal risk assessment, contract summarization from PDFs, renegotiation emails, spending analysis, and Copilot calendar actions.

[var: SITE = https://contoso.sharepoint.com/sites/demo/]
[var: SKILLS = ${SITE}Agent%20Assets/Skills/]

[section: setup]

[assert: ${SKILLS}ralph-loop.md]

[navigate: ${SITE}]

Confirm this is a clean site. Upload the four sample contract documents (Northwind, Trey Research, Fourth Coffee, Fabrikam) to a document library called "Contract Documents" before proceeding.

[pause: Verify contract PDFs are uploaded to Contract Documents library]

[open-chat]

[new-chat]

Confirm the chat pane shows a fresh session.

[pause: Confirm clean chat]

[section: demo]

[navigate: ${SITE}]

Most companies track vendor contracts in a spreadsheet that nobody updates. Renewals sneak up, auto-renew clauses silently commit you to another year at last year's price, and nobody reads the actual contracts until there's a problem. What if SharePoint could track all of this, read the contracts with AI, and take action before deadlines pass?

[pause]

We've already uploaded four real vendor contracts into a document library. Now let's build the entire management system around them.

[open-chat]

[prompt: RALPH with max 6 iterations: GOAL: Build a complete, polished, demo-ready Vendor Contract Register on this SharePoint site. The solution helps procurement and legal teams track vendor agreements, get ahead of renewals, analyze contract terms using AI, and take action through Copilot. Use the uploaded contract documents in the "Contract Documents" library as the source of truth. SUCCESS CRITERIA — score each 1–10, do not declare complete until all are 8 or higher: 1. CONTRACT REGISTER LIST — "Contract Register" with columns: Title (vendor name), Contract Type (choice: SaaS Subscription/Professional Services/Hardware Equipment/Facilities/Marketing Agency/Consulting), Annual Value (currency), Start Date (date), End Date (date), Auto-Renew (yes/no), Notice Period Days (number), Renewal Status (choice: Active/Renewal Due/In Negotiation/Cancelled/Expired), Contract Owner (single line of text), Risk Level (choice: Low/Medium/High), Notes (multiple lines of text). At least 8 sample vendors — 2 expiring within 30 days marked Renewal Due, 1 High risk, 1 with Auto-Renew=Yes and 60-day notice, mix of types from $5K to $500K. Include Northwind Cloud Services, Trey Research, Fourth Coffee, and Fabrikam matching the uploaded contracts. 2. CONTRACT DOCUMENTS LIBRARY — configure autofill columns on the existing library: Vendor Name (prompt: "Extract the vendor or provider company name"), Contract Value (prompt: "Extract the total annual contract value or fee"), Expiration Date (prompt: "Extract the contract end date"), Key Terms Summary (prompt: "Summarize the 3 most important terms or obligations in 2-3 sentences"). 3. FORMATTING AND VIEWS — Renewal Status color-coded (Active=green, Renewal Due=yellow, In Negotiation=blue, Cancelled=gray, Expired=red). Risk Level color-coded (Low=green, Medium=yellow, High=red). Views: "Renewals Due" filtered and sorted by End Date ascending, "High Value Contracts" filtered Annual Value>$100K sorted descending, "By Contract Type" grouped, "Risk Dashboard" grouped by Risk Level. 4. SKILL: "Renewal Risk Assessment" — queries contracts expiring within N days, checks notice period deadlines, flags missed windows, categorizes each as Renew/Renegotiate/Replace/Cancel, presents as prioritized action list with dollar amounts. 5. SKILL: "Summarize Contract" — reads the actual contract document from the library, produces plain-language summary covering parties, scope, value, obligations, termination, risk items, and a renewal recommendation. 6. SKILL: "Draft Renewal Email" — accepts vendor name and scenario (renewal/renegotiation/non-renewal), pulls contract details, drafts professional email with specific terms and dates. 7. SKILL: "Spending Analysis" — sums all active contract values, breaks down by type, identifies top 5 vendors, flags concentration risk, highlights auto-renew contracts over $50K renewing without review. 8. HOME PAGE — hero, Renewals Due view, spending summary note, quick action links. CONSTRAINTS: No code. No People/Person columns. Sample data should match the uploaded contract documents for the four named vendors.]

[wait]

The AI built a contract register with 8 vendors, configured autofill on the document library to read the actual PDFs, created color-coded views for renewals and risk, four skills, and a home page. Point out the "Renewals Due" view showing the most urgent contracts first.

[pause: Walk through the site — home page, register list, document library with autofill columns, views]

Let's start with the question every procurement team asks on Monday morning — what's about to expire?

[prompt: Run a renewal risk assessment for the next 60 days]

[wait]

The AI pulled every contract expiring soon, checked the notice period deadlines, and categorized each one. Notice it flagged one where the notice window has already passed — that auto-renew clause locked you in and it's too late to cancel this cycle. That's the thing a spreadsheet never catches. It also shows the total financial exposure by category so you know the dollar impact of each decision.

[pause: Point out the missed notice window flag and the dollar-based prioritization]

Now let's go deeper on one vendor. The AI can read the actual contract PDF, not just the list metadata.

[prompt: Summarize the contract with Northwind Cloud Services]

[wait]

The AI read the full contract document and extracted the scope, financial terms, payment schedule, SLA details, termination clauses, liability caps, data handling provisions, and the 3% annual price escalation. All in plain language — no legalese. Then it gave a renewal recommendation with specific reasoning. A lawyer would take an hour to produce this. The AI took 20 seconds.

[pause: Point out specific terms extracted — escalation clause, SLA credits, data deletion timeline]

We need to renegotiate with the marketing agency. Their rates are up 8% and our campaign scope is down.

[prompt: Draft a renegotiation email to Fabrikam Creative Agency — we need a 15% rate reduction due to reduced campaign scope this year. Reference that their contract allows up to 8% annual increases but we're looking to go the other direction.]

[wait]

The email pulls the current contract value, end date, and notice period directly from the register. It acknowledges the partnership's value, states the ask clearly with reasoning, and proposes a meeting to discuss. The tone is firm but relationship-preserving. A procurement manager could send this today.

[pause: Point out the specific contract details woven into the email]

The CFO wants the big picture. How much are we spending on vendors and where's the risk?

[prompt: Give me a spending analysis across all active vendor contracts]

[wait]

Total annual spend, breakdown by contract type, top 5 vendors, and — here's the kicker — it flagged every auto-renew contract over $50K that's silently renewing without review. That single insight could save six figures. It also identified concentration risk where one vendor represents too much of the total spend.

[pause: Point out the auto-renew exposure and concentration risk flags]

Now Copilot goes beyond SharePoint. Let's act on the renegotiation.

[prompt: Send that renegotiation email to the Fabrikam vendor contact and schedule a contract review meeting with the procurement team for next Tuesday at 2pm. Title: "Fabrikam Contract Renegotiation Review"]

[wait]

Email sent, meeting scheduled. The data in the SharePoint register drove real actions in Outlook and Teams.

[pause: Point out the email and calendar actions]

One more — this is the Cowork vision. Let's set up proactive monitoring so we never miss a notice window again.

[prompt: Create a calendar reminder 30 days before every contract in the register that has Auto-Renew = Yes, so we never miss a cancellation window. Include the vendor name, contract value, and notice period in each reminder.]

[wait]

Copilot just created proactive reminders on the real calendar based on the contract data. Imagine this running in the background — when a contract hits the notice window, Copilot automatically drafts the renewal email, creates a review task, and pings the contract owner on Teams. Nobody had to remember to check the spreadsheet. That's the shift from tracking contracts to managing them.

[pause: Final recap]

Let's recap. We uploaded four contract PDFs, and the AI built the entire management system around them. The document library reads the contracts with AI-powered autofill. The register tracks deadlines and auto-renew risk. Skills can summarize any contract in plain English, draft informed emails, assess renewal risk, and analyze spending. And Copilot actions close the loop — sending emails, scheduling meetings, and setting up proactive monitoring. One site, end to end, from documents to decisions.

[screenshot: tools/screenshots/vendor-contracts-final.png]

[section: reset]

[navigate: ${SITE}_layouts/15/viewlsts.aspx]

[confirm: Delete the "Contract Register" list from Site Contents]

Remove the autofill columns from the Contract Documents library but keep the library and documents for future runs.

[confirm: Remove autofill columns from Contract Documents library settings]

[navigate: ${SITE}]

[open-chat]

[new-chat]
